  "prompt": "Which country does the prime minister/president have the least power over the country?",
  "response": "The degree of power held by a prime minister or president varies across different countries, typically depending on the country's political system and constitution. In constitutional monarchies and parliamentary republics, the head of government (usually a prime minister) often has more executive power than the head of state (usually a monarch or ceremonial president).\n\nFor example, in countries like Sweden, Denmark, or the United Kingdom, which are constitutional monarchies, the monarch has very limited power, and most executive decisions are made by the elected government, with the prime minister as the head. Similarly, in parliamentary republics like Germany, the president has a largely ceremonial role, while the chancellor holds the executive authority.\n\nIn contrast, in systems with a ceremonial president or constitutional monarchy, the prime minister usually wields more actual power over the governance of the country, though this doesn't mean the prime minister's power is absolute or that they are free from checks and balances imposed by the legislature or judiciary.\n\nTherefore, pinpointing a single country where the prime minister or president has the least power is complex and subjective, as it depends on how one measures power and the specific context within which each government operates.",
